'''Edith Balas''' is a Professor of Art History, College of Humanities & Social Sciences at [[Carnegie Mellon University]] in [[Pittsburgh]], [[Pennsylvania]].  Born June 20, 1929 in [[Cluj]], [[Romania]], she is a [[Holocaust survivor]], art professor, and [[historian]]. She is married to mathematician [[Egon Balas]], also a retired professor at Carnegie Mellon.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://holocaustcenterpgh.org/exhibitions/in-celebration-of-life-living-legacy-project/edith-balas/|title=Holocaust Center of Pittsburgh » Edith Balas|website=holocaustcenterpgh.org|accessdate=8 October 2017}}</ref>

Balas' main areas of interest are [[modern art]] (1890-1960), painting and sculpture, and the art of the Italian Renaissance.<ref name="Beck review">{{cite journal|last1=Beck|first1=James|title=Review: Michelangelo's Medici Chapel: A New Interpretation. Edith Balas|journal=Renaissance Quarterly|date=July 1998|volume=51|issue=2|pages=620–621|doi=10.2307/2901595}}</ref><ref name="Emison">{{cite journal|last1=Emison|first1=Patricia|title=Review: Michelangelo’s Double Self-Portraits by Edith Balas|journal=Renaissance Quarterly|date=June 2005|volume=58|issue=2|pages=600–602|doi=10.1353/ren.2008.0719}}</ref><ref name="Feinstein">{{cite journal|last1=Feinstein|first1=Steve|title=The Holocaust in the Painting of Valentin Lustig (review)|journal=Shofar: An Interdisciplinary Journal of Jewish Studies|date=2003|volume=21|issue=3|pages=190–192|doi=10.1353/sho.2003.0013}}</ref><ref name="Painter goes deep into both Holocaust history and his own story">{{cite web|last1=Thomas|first1=Mary|title=Art Reviews: Painter goes deep into both Holocaust history and his own story|url=http://old.post-gazette.com/ae/20020119thomas0119fnp6.asp|website=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|accessdate=9 October 2017}}</ref> In 2003, she curated an exhibition at the Frick Art Museum,<ref name="Frick exhibits explore two artists' sense of loss">{{cite web|last1=Thomas|first1=Mary|title=Art Review: Frick exhibits explore two artists' sense of loss|url=http://old.post-gazette.com/ae/20031021frick1021p3.asp|website=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|accessdate=9 October 2017}}</ref> and several in Pittsburgh, Paris, New York and Budapest. She has been teaching at [[Carnegie Mellon University]] since 1977, and is also an Adjunct Professor of History of Art and Architecture at the [[University of Pittsburgh]].

Edith Balas is also a Holocaust survivor, having been sent to the Nazi death camp [[Auschwitz]].  In ''Bird in Flight: Memoir of a Survivor and Scholar,''  Balas tells her story of facing grim situations and becoming what she describes as a “professional survivor.”  Balas named her memoir “Bird in Flight” after [[Constantin Brâncuși]]’s famous sculpture of the same name. “I consider it emblematic of my life,” she said.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cmu.edu/news/archive/2011/March/march22_edithbalasmemoir.shtml|title=March 22: CMU's Edith Balas Pens Memoir Depicting Life as a Survivor and Scholar - Carnegie Mellon University - CMU|first=Carnegie Mellon University|last=(CMU)|website=www.cmu.edu|accessdate=8 October 2017}}</ref>

After the war her husband was imprisoned by the [[Communist Romania|communist authorities]] for three years, during which Balas raised their two daughters. She received an M.A. in Philosophy from the [[University of Bucharest]] in 1952.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cmu.edu/cas/people/balas_edith.html|title=Edith Balas - Center for the Arts in Society - Carnegie Mellon University|first=Carnegie Mellon|last=University|website=www.cmu.edu|accessdate=8 October 2017}}</ref> She then emigrated to the United States with her husband, and received an M.A. in the History of Arts from Pittsburgh University in 1970 and a Ph.D. in 1973.

